The commen- tators bring up from Macrobius (Sat. vi. 3), “Non si mihi linguae Centum atque ora sient totidem vocesque liquatae,'' which he quotes from the Histric war of Hostius, a poet of whom little is known. No one who considers the poverty of the Latin Epic ean be surprised at this common- place bombast being often repeated. We have it in Silius Italicus, who was a con- temporary of Persius. The Scholiast quotes Horace, “Aut labentis equo descripsit vulnera Parthi '’ (S. ii. 1. 15) 3 he therefore under- stood it differently, supposing the man to be wounded and to draw the point of the arrow that shot him from his groin. This I think is right. Casaubon and Jahn take ‘vulnera' actively‚ but ‘ferri' for an ar- row hanging in its quiver by the man’s side. The poems on the Parthians writ- ten in Persius’ time, no doubt, were as full of falsehoods as those which may have suggested Horace's line above quoted.
